Based on the search results, here's what you need to know about Tailwind CSS v4 configuration and the `tailwind.config.js` file:

## Major Changes in v4

One of the biggest changes in Tailwind CSS v4.0 is the shift from configuring your project in JavaScript to configuring it in CSS. Released in January 2025, it replaces the JavaScript-based configuration system with a CSS-first approach, introduces a new high-performance engine built on Lightning CSS, and adds first-class support for modern CSS features like cascade layers, container queries, and 3D transforms.

## No More tailwind.config.js by Default

Instead of a tailwind.config.js file, you can configure all of your customizations directly in the CSS file where you import Tailwind, giving you one less file to worry about in your project.

## New CSS-First Configuration

The new CSS-first configuration lets you do just about everything you could do in your tailwind.config.js file, including configuring your design tokens, defining custom utilities and variants, and more. You now use the `@theme` directive in your CSS to define configuration:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  --color-primary: hsl(49, 100%, 7%);
  --color-link: hsl(49, 100%, 7%);
}
```

## If You Still Need tailwind.config.js

If your project still needs a traditional config file, don't worry. Tailwind hasn't removed support for it entirely. You can manually create tailwind.config.js and link it in your CSS file.

## Performance Improvements

Tailwind v4 moves everything to CSS-first configuration using a new @theme directive, and the speed improvements are kind of ridiculous—we're talking 3-10x faster full builds and up to 100x faster incremental rebuilds.


